ving productivity improvement.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36.85pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q14 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mr Bain</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> If we can take that point a little further, the ONS has published new data this morning and that indicates that of the last nine quarters productivity has fallen in this country in seven of them.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">At a time when the pressure from unit labour costs is hardly high and hours worked in the economy are now higher than they were in 2008, do we not have a really serious problem here and what is the strategy of the Government to address this?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Vince </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Cable:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> We have a serious problem if it continues, but the poor productivity performance is a flipside of having a relatively favourable performance on employment.</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> But</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> if we are going to go forward, you are perfectly right</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> productivity has now to improve.</span><span style="font-f